Discover how startups are leveraging artificial intelligence to redefine th=
eir go-to-market approach and stay ahead of the curve. This comprehensive g=
uide covers everything from customer acquisition to scaling operations with=
 AI. Don't miss out on the insights that can transform your business.
Download now and get ahead in the AI revolution!
(1) GPT-4o [ https://substack.com/redirect/4f72a48f-d79b-4b42-9c94-db29072a=
d752?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
By this point, you=E2=80=99ve likely already been inundated with Chat-GPT4o=
 demos and threads, but we still think it=E2=80=99s important to emphasize =
just how magical some of these highlights are. The major updates from OpenA=
I=E2=80=99s Spring Update were that the company launched its desktop app, r=
eleased its latest model Chat-GPT4o, and is making this model freely access=
ible to users. In my view, the main advancement with GPT4o is that it=E2=80=
=99s much faster and smoother across multiple modalities. On the surface, t=
his may not seem like much =E2=80=94 reducing latency isn=E2=80=99t the sex=
iest thing ever =E2=80=94 but it unlocks certain types of interactions with=
 AI that we=E2=80=99re previously to clunky to enjoy.=20
Take, for example, tutoring. Previous versions of Chat-GPT could certainly =
be helpful in helping a student on math problems, but you couldn=E2=80=99t =
really imagine an elementary school student using Chat-GPT as a personalize=
d tutor. Well, with GPT4o it now actually seems pretty natural. As Noah Smi=
th pointed out [ https://substack.com/redirect/ad4e0d19-3c47-463d-a540-4c63=
157ddf78?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ], this demo basically shows we invented the illustrated primer from =E2=
=80=9CDiamond Age=E2=80=9D (and just 30 years after the book was written.)
But it=E2=80=99s not just tutoring. With GPT4o, there=E2=80=99s a whole sle=
w of capabilities that now seem more natural due to the reduced latency and=
 multi-modal flexibility of the model. All of the most recent GPT models ha=
ve been able to translate language, but GPT4o can do so using voice and wit=
h the necessary speed to allow conversations to flow naturally.=20
GPT4o was certainly not GPT5 (or at least what people expect out of GPT5), =
but these improvements in speed and flexibility will make AI more human-lik=
e and ultimately more useful. Intelligence is only as good as our ability t=
o use it.=20
(2) Neuralink=E2=80=99s First Patient: =E2=80=98It Blows My Mind So Much=E2=
=80=99 [ https://substack.com/redirect/aef9b4f9-63a2-4713-9244-77149e546218=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Ashlee Vance for Bloomberg
Arbaugh named his implant Eve in part, he says, because God presented Eve t=
o Adam as his helper. Recently, he=E2=80=99s begun tracing letters on his c=
omputer screen with a cursor he controls through the implant. It=E2=80=99s =
the first stage of training Neuralink=E2=80=99s software to recognize the w=
ords that Arbaugh is thinking. The hope for Arbaugh is that he=E2=80=99ll s=
oon be able to think entire sentences and have the software know what he=E2=
=80=99s trying to say. He=E2=80=99s long dreamed of being a fantasy writer =
and would like to write a novel.
A few months ago, we covered the story of the first public patient to recei=
ve a Neuralink implant. The videos [ https://substack.com/redirect/7869135f=
-58b8-42c3-9152-1010954afee1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] of the patient, Nolan Arbaugh, playing video games w=
ith his brain went viral. A few months on, Arbaugh reports that the Neurali=
nk brain implant has changed his life.
Ashlee Vance of Bloomberg Businessweek profiled Arbaugh =E2=80=94 how he en=
ded up paralyzed, how we stumbled his way into becoming a celebrity cyborg,=
 and what his life is like today thanks to Nueralink.
Consider this story your gentle reminder that Elon Musk=E2=80=99s third or =
fourth most notable project is currently transforming the lives of disabled=
 folks and has the potential to totally transform how humans interact with =
computers and the world around us.=20
But the emerald mines!!!
(3) The Bot Company [ https://substack.com/redirect/b668bafa-92a6-43f3-b617=
-6cf37bd1dd88?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ]
Former Cruise founder and CEO Kyle Voigt announced his next company which p=
lans to use AI and robots to build bots that do chores for you. He didn=E2=
=80=99t share much about the company beyond the general mission and stacked=
 cap table, but you can imagine the team is working on something like a (ma=
ybe humanoid) robot that is specifically designed to do household work like=
 doing the dishes, taking out the trash, and folding laundry. Strong Rosie =
from the Jetsons vibes.=20
I personally spend about one hour per day on household chores between clean=
ing, laundry, cooking, and sprucing =E2=80=94 and I live in a 1BR apartment=
 in New York. The average woman in the U.S. spends over 2 hours per day on =
household chores. I am sure there are plenty of folks out there that value =
their time at or above $25/hr and would be willing to spend $50/day or $1,5=
00/mo or $18,000/year in order to get hours back that would=E2=80=99ve othe=
rwise been spent on household chores. With those numbers, the chorebot mark=
et starts to look a lot like the car market.
What=E2=80=99s more striking than any one bot company is just how many ther=
e seem to be. On Wednesday, OpenAI=E2=80=99s Evan Morikawa tweeted that he=
=E2=80=99s teaming up with two robotics people to launch a new company, pre=
sumably building robots.=20
Maybe we=E2=80=99re in a robotics bubble, but this is the kind of productiv=
e bubble we=E2=80=99re here for. Whether in this cycle or the next, we=E2=
=80=99ll have dozens of genius-run companies competing to give us the lowes=
t-cost, highest-performance robots they can to do all the work =E2=80=94 li=
ke laundry, dishes, box-packing, heavy object lifting, whatever =E2=80=94 t=
hat we don=E2=80=99t want to do. All this capital and talent will speed up =
development and spin up supply chains. There will be some absolutely massiv=
e winners =E2=80=94 labor is a $45 trillion market globally =E2=80=94 but c=
onsumers will be the biggest winners of all.=20
(4) GLP-1-directed NMDA receptor antagonism for obesity treatment [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/b3281f56-564b-4bf3-8d4c-58cfe05db3b5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Petersen et al in Nature
In summary, our approach demonstrates the feasibility of using peptide-medi=
ated targeting to achieve cell-specific ionotropic receptor modulation and =
highlights the therapeutic potential of unimolecular mixed GLP-1 receptor a=
gonism and NMDA receptor antagonism for safe and effective obesity treatmen=
t.
At this point, we=E2=80=99re all pretty aware of how effective GLP-1s are a=
s an obesity treatment =E2=80=94 frankly, more effective than really anyone=
 could have imagined just a few years ago. But we may be at the very beginn=
ing of this story.  A new drug that combines a gut-hormone-mimicking peptid=
e with a small molecule and targets the brain cells controlling appetite ha=
s shown promising results and may potentially outperforming existing GLP-1s=
=2E
The novel drug employs a =E2=80=9CTrojan Horse=E2=80=9D strategy by hiding =
a small molecule that blocks the NMDA receptor within a gut-hormone-mimicki=
ng peptide used in GLP-1s. This allows the drug to specifically target and =
act on neurons in the brain that regulate appetite, potentially enhancing w=
eight-loss effects while minimizing side effects. We=E2=80=99re still only =
working with mice here, but damn, those are some skinny mice.=20
(5) =E2=80=98Quantum internet=E2=80=99 demonstration in cities is most adva=
nced yet [ https://substack.com/redirect/f566bd3e-6a7a-4019-a51b-7be94eb338=
05?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Davide Castelvecchi for Nature
Three separate research groups have demonstrated quantum entanglement =E2=
=80=94 in which two or more objects are linked so that they contain the sam=
e information even if they are far apart =E2=80=94 over several kilometres =
of existing optical fibres in real urban areas. The feat is a key step towa=
rds a future quantum internet [ https://substack.com/redirect/77c0ceff-97b3=
-48c3-b6f6-0bee4b1e026e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], a network that could allow information to be exchanged w=
hile encoded in quantum states.
Quantum internet here we come! Three separate research groups demonstrated =
quantum entanglement over several kilometers of existing optical fibers in =
real urban areas, accomplishing a major milestone towards creating a quantu=
m internet: transmitting information encoded in quantum states.
But what is the quantum internet? It promises nearly unbreakable cryptograp=
hic security and the ability to connect quantum computers into a powerful n=
etwork. It could also enable advanced scientific experiments, like creating=
 extensive telescope networks with unparalleled resolution.
The quantum internet is still in the early stages and needs to overcome som=
e significant technical challenges =E2=80=94 with estimated practical rollo=
uts not happening for at least a decade =E2=80=94 but this entanglement rep=
resents a quantum leap in the development of the quantum internet. Get it?
Bonus: Senate Votes to Overturn SAB 121 [ https://substack.com/redirect/84d=
50617-670f-4c2c-b3f4-b035c46297c0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Packy here. I love the smell of the democratic process working in the morni=
ng!=20
Yesterday, the Senate voted to repeal the SEC=E2=80=99s Staff Accounting Bu=
lletin No. 121 (SAB 121), which Gary Gensler=E2=80=99s SEC hastily rushed o=
ut in April 2022. SAB 121 directed companies that custody digital assets to=
 record them as liabilities on their balance sheets, along with the corresp=
onding assets, which made it more difficult for banks to offer crypto custo=
dy services. Which was Gensler=E2=80=99s point: SAB 121 was part of an effo=
rt to cut crypto off from the traditional banking system.=20
Republicans, led by Congressman Patrick McHenry in the House and Senator Cy=
nthia Lummis in the Senate, introduced a bill to overturn SAB 121 because G=
ensler=E2=80=99s SEC issued it without consulting regulators like the Fed, =
didn=E2=80=99t go through the standard notice-and-comment process, and beca=
use while the SEC characterized it as =E2=80=9Cguidance,=E2=80=9D a Governm=
ent Accountability Office report found that it constituted a new rule that =
should have been approved by Congress.=20
What made yesterday=E2=80=99s vote particularly notable was that 12 Democra=
tic Senators, including Chuck Schumer, Cory Booker, and Kristen Gillibrand,=
 crossed the aisle to vote to repeal SAB 121. That=E2=80=99s a healthy dose=
 of egg on the face of Senator Elizabeth Warren and the latest in a series =
of losses for Gensler. Turns out, this is America, and there are laws and p=
rocesses that even the most ambitious regulators must follow.=20
Now, it=E2=80=99s up to President Biden to sign it. He originally vowed to =
veto the resolution, but given that so many powerful party members broke ra=
nks, vetoing it now would be a weird move sure to lose him whatever crypto =
community support he has left. Just sign it, Joe.=20
Pro-Innovation Bipartisanship. You love to see it. Maybe wagmi after all.=
=20
